title: For Sale:  RARE Schwarzlose Model 1908 Blow Forward 32 Pistol
location: North Carolina, North Carolina, United States
postcontent: RARE and Important Schwarzlose Model 1908 "Blow-Forward" Pistol in .32 acpAccessories:One 6rd Magazine Additional Information:This A.W. Schwarzlose blow-forward semi-automatic pistol came in from an estate. It is chambered in 7.65mm (32 acp) caliber, has a 50% blued finish, S/N is 5521, checkered hard rubber grips, and is in overall good original condition. The hammer is a little sticky but everything does function. This is one of the scarcest German semi-automatic pistols made, and an important piece for the system collector as there are only a couple models of blow-forward actions. The Schwarzlose Model 1908 was a semi-automatic pistol, designed by Andreas Schwarzlose, released in 1908 in German Empire and produced until 1911. The Schwarzlose employs a very distinctive "blow-forward action" operating mechanism. It has no slide, instead the mechanism is operated by the barrel being projected forward due to the gas pressure and the friction of the bullet passing through the bore, the compressed recoil spring drives the barrel back, stripping the top cartridge from the magazine, chambering the round, and pressing the cartridge head against the standing breech, which is part of the frame. Andreas Schwarzlose (best known for his 1907 and 07/12 machine guns) designed this pistol for military and civilian use, and it saw minor commercial success. The blow-forward action was pretty much a developmental dead end, because it made for unusually sharp recoil and was potentially unsafe to handle – the only three commercially available pistols made this way were the Hino, the Schwarzlose, and the Mannlicher 1894 (which was quickly replaced by better Mannlicher designs). The Swiss did tinker a bit with a blow-forward action in their AK-52/53 rifle as well, but this ultimately went nowhere.Shipping is $15

title: For Sale:  1895 Finnish Captured Russian M91 Imperial Tula Dragoon - Rare
postcontent: Very rare antique, only other one I found on gunbroker sold for about $3000 in the completed auctions, but I would say this one is even more unique.. https://www.gunbroker.com/item/750002325 About 90% bluing. Dragoon marked sights. The buttplate says "27" which could be off of an M28 stock, civil guard, or maybe the 27th Jager battalion. It also has a "1" inscribed under the buttplate. Finnish wartime round finger spliced stock. Nice tiger striping on handguard, arctic birch stock. KAB marked rear sight indicating cossack or Dragoon. It is a bit shorter than a regular M91. This was most likely used in the winter war, Finnish civil war, world war I, and WWII, if not all. It's counter bored, no import mark. I have shot it about 5 times and is a consistent shooter, but still would only buy as a collectible and not something to eat a bunch of lead. This is probably a bring-back since there's no import mark. It has the Finnish army SA mark on the side of the barrel shank, imperial tula crest, tang matches receiver and marked 1895 so this considered antique and requires no FFL to sell, but I will not ship. Only trades I'm iterested are Suomi KP31's, M1 Garrands/Carbins(depending on make & condition), Swedish or German mausers, Swiss K31's, FN49's, Russian SKS's, SVT-40's, Romaian PSL's, other mosins, M1917 revolvers, WWII pistols, - Pretty much anything WWII/WWI and/or slight-postwar military weapons.
